  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improving access to tech&amp;fin services in mining sector in Ghana</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Ghana, we want to improve the quality and the availability of services that promote responsible mining. In 2020, 5 Service Providers were supported  to develop strong businesses and deliver best practice services to mines. They were introduced to 30 mines and by the end of 2020 they were providing services to 12 mines. Triggered by the Governmental Multi-sectoral Mining Integrated Project (MMIP), that encourages sustainable development of Artisanal and Small-Scale Mining, mines show increasing interest in working with local Service Providers on topics as Mine planning and mechanization, Land Reclamation and Revegetation and Exploration and Reserve Estimation. Working conditions of 1,069 miners have improved considerably, resulting in a significant decrease (80%) of reported occupational accidents. Now miners count with protective clothing and adhere to safety requirements, safety signs have been installed in the mines and there are daily informal meetings around safety topics. By the end of 2020, 7 of the supported mines operate in line with the CRAFT Code, keeping records of financial and workforce data, and use traceability systems to track the volume of responsibly produced gold. A gold trading company and a refinery have committed to source CRAFT compliant gold from these mines. We reached 4,069 small scale gold miners via our Gold Interactive Voice response digital tool (IVR) and trained them to implement responsible mining practices. This proved effective to reach miners despite the travel and meeting restrictions. We have engaged with three local financial institutions that are willing to consider providing finance to ASMs. At the same time we are supporting interested mines to build the capacity and documentation to meet the requirements for accessing finance.</narrative>
  </description>
